The car tuner brought the voice of the digital soul
Everything you know about obesity is wrong, according to the headline of a long text written by Michael Hobbes for the Huffington Post and photographed by Finlay Mackay. The provocative explanation says that the medical community for decades ignored the facts about obesity and waged a ruthless (and also useless) war against overweight people, which not only affected public opinion but also destroyed many lives. But now is the time for a new paradigm.
What Hobbes states at the outset is the fact that there is often a very long and tedious journey from knowing the facts to putting them into practice. He mentions the case of scurvy, where some captains handed out lemons, limes and oranges to their crew in the seventeenth century, believing that they would prevent diseases. However, the British Navy withdrew from this practice due to fears of increased costs. The clear influence of the fruit in the prevention and treatment of the disease was then demonstrated in the middle of the 18th century, but it took another fifty years before the navy took it into account. Seat belts also existed long before the invention of the car, but became mandatory only in the 1960s, as did the first confirmed asbestos-related death in 1906, yet its first ban came in 1973.
&quot;Every discovery in the field of public health - no matter how important - has always had to compete with traditions, prejudices and financial incentives within the society in which it was to be implemented,&quot; Hobbes writes. In American society today, nearly 80 percent of the adult population and about one-third of children meet the definition of overweight or obesity. More Americans today live with obesity than with breast cancer, Alzheimer&#39;s, Parkinson&#39;s and HIV combined.
At the same time, obesity is seen as a sovereign personal failure of an individual, which is said to burden the health care system and reduce GDP. The fear of obesity is so great in the population that Americans today spend more money on diets than they spend on computer games and movies. However, the truth is that diets do not work. As early as 1959, research showed that 95 to 98% of attempts to lose weight end in failure, and two-thirds of people on a diet then gain more than they lose.
Armed with statistics, Hobbes further describes the lifestyles and traumas of overweight people. The personal one encounters the systemic one, where, for example, at the faculties, when teaching future doctors, he devotes only 19 hours of the entire study to the issue of nutrition. Which, at a time when the 60 calorie process that Americans receive comes from ultra-processed food.
How obesity is stigmatized is again illustrated by reports from surgeries, where overweight people usually experience shorter check-ups, doctors approach them with less empathy and consider them more problematic patients.
However, being overweight is far from just an American problem, Hobbes writes. Since 1980, the proportion of obesity in 73 countries has doubled and has risen in 113. And during that time, no country has managed to reduce and stop this increase. Absolutely none.
