Microplasts reached the human gut, the study confirmed for the first time
Scientists have been confirmed for several years. A team led by Professor Philipp Schwabl, a professor at the University of Vienna, has published a study which for the first time proves the presence of microplastics in human stool. Although the study is small, with eight participants from Europe, Japan and Russia - however, in the samples of all subjects, small particles of plastic with dimensions between 50 and 500 micrometers were found. None of the eight subjects were vegetarians, six of them did not avoid sea fish, all drank water from plastic bottles and food packed in plastic.
And it would actually be a bit of a miracle if nothing was found. We already know that microplastics - which are either produced directly, for example for the cosmetics industry, or are formed by the disintegration of larger pieces - are present in marine animals, insects, tap water and lemonades; in short, everywhere on the planet. Thus, their entry into the human digestive tract has only been officially confirmed. There were about 20 microplast particles per ten grams of stool, and scientists estimate that more than half of the world&#39;s population will have them.
Lay and scientific awareness, of course, suspects that it is not good. However, humanity still does not know how bad it is - and what effect microplastics have on &quot;host&quot; organisms. Small particles can enter the bloodstream or lymphatic system and end up in the liver, for example. &quot;This is the first study of its kind to confirm what we have thought for a long time. Now that we have the first evidence of microplastics in the human body, we must continue to investigate what exactly this means for human health,&quot; says Schwabl.
So far, it is known that microplastics in the intestines can negatively affect the immune reactions of the digestive system, and thus facilitate the absorption of toxic chemicals and other pathogens into the body. And so far no other known solution is to limit the use of plastics, especially polypropylene. However, this will be difficult - the first task facing governments and authorities will at least stop its sharp rise. As for plastic bottles alone, experts estimate that in three years, humanity will consume a fifth more than they do today. The current rate is captivating one million bottles bought per minute. About eight million tons of plastic end up in the seas and oceans every year. Waste threatens marine ecosystems and infects the digestive systems of marine animals.
Some states have already adopted restrictions and other measures, for example, Kenya has banned plastic bags under the threat of draconian penalties. The European Commission is considering minor bans (well-known straws), and the domestic Ministry of the Environment is heading in the same direction. However, critics claim that such measures are nice, but completely inadequate.
